The International Day for the Elimination of Poverty (WDSJ) is celebrated on October 17 every year around the world. This day was officially recognized by the United Nations as an international holiday in Resolution A/RES/47/196 of December 22, 1992.
The first "International Day for the Elimination of Poverty" took place in Paris, France, on October 17, 1987. On this day, about 100,000 people gathered at the "Place of Human Rights and Freedoms" in Piazza Trocadéro, Paris. , France. , in honor of the victims of poverty, violence and fear, at the call of priest Joseph Wresinski (1917–1988) 

The United Nations has designated 20 November as International Children's Day but leaves member states to choose their own Children's Day. Several countries of the former Soviet Union have celebrated International Children's Day on June 1. Many countries celebrate Children's Day on other dates.

Himeji Castle is an ancient Japanese castle in the city of Himeji, Hyōgo Prefecture.

It is one of the oldest surviving structures in Japan, representing the citadels of modern Japan. Himeji was recognized by UNESCO as a world heritage (cultural) in 1993 and a special historical site of Japan. Various parts of Himeji Castle have been designated as national treasures or important cultural heritage sites of the nation. Himeji Castle, together with Matsumoto Castle and Kumamoto Castle, is known as the "Three Kingdoms Treasure Castle" of Japan.
name: Himeji Castle Japan
